hands_on_practices.problem:
In digital signal processing, an 'upsampler' is a system that increases the sampling rate of a signal by an integer factor $L$. This process is a fundamental part of interpolation. The upsampler operates by inserting $L-1$ zero-valued samples between each consecutive pair of samples from the original signal.

The mathematical relationship between an input signal $x[n]$ and the corresponding output signal $y[n]$ from an upsampler is given by:
$$
y[n] = \begin{cases} 
x[n/L] & \text{if } n \text{ is an integer multiple of } L \\ 
0 & \text{otherwise} 
\end{cases}
$$
Consider a discrete-time input signal defined as $x[n] = (4 - n) u[n]$, where $u[n]$ is the discrete-time unit step function (defined as $u[n]=1$ for $n \ge 0$ and $u[n]=0$ for $n < 0$). This signal is processed by an upsampler with an upsampling factor of $L=3$.

Determine the sequence of the first 10 samples of the output signal $y[n]$, corresponding to the indices $n = 0, 1, 2, \dots, 9$. Present your answer as a sequence of these 10 numerical values.
